Definition 1.6. An object $E$ of a ${\mathbf{k}}$-linear triangulated category ${{\mathcal{T}}}$ is called exceptional if ${\operatorname{Hom}}(E,E[p])=0$ when $p\neq 0,$ and ${\operatorname{Hom}}(E,E)={\mathbf{k}}.$ An exceptional collection in ${{\mathcal{T}}}$ is a sequence of exceptional objects $(E_{0},\dots,E_{n})$ satisfying the semiorthogonality condition ${\operatorname{Hom}}(E_{i},E_{j}[p])=0$ for all $p$ when $i>j.$
Definition 1.8. We define triangulated categories of singularities ${\mathbf{D}}_{\rm Sg}^{\rm gr}({A})$ and ${\mathbf{D}}_{\rm Sg}({A})$ as the quotient ${\mathbf{D}}^{b}({\operatorname{gr}\!-A})/{\mathbf{D}}^{b}({\operatorname{% grproj}\!-A})$ and ${\mathbf{D}}^{b}({\operatorname{mod}\!-A})/{\mathbf{D}}^{b}({\operatorname{% proj}\!-A})$ respectively.
Definition 3.1. The category $\operatorname{DGrB}(W)$ constructed above will be called the category of graded D-branes of type B for the pair $(B=\bigoplus_{i\geq 0}B_{i},W).$
