Definition 1.3. Let $D$ be in ${\mathcal{C}}$. A weak Yang-Baxter operator is a morphism $t_{D,D}:D\otimes D\rightarrow D\otimes D$ in ${\mathcal{C}}$ such that: (a1) $t_{D,D}$ satisfies the Yang-Baxter equation. (a2) There exists an idempotent morphism $\nabla_{D,D}:D\otimes D\rightarrow D\otimes D$ satisfying the following identities: (a2-1) $(\nabla_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes\nabla_{D,D})=(D\otimes\nabla_{D,D})\circ% (\nabla_{D,D}\otimes D),$ (a2-2) $(\nabla_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D})=(D\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(\nabla_% {D,D}\otimes D),$ (a2-3) $(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes\nabla_{D,D})=(D\otimes\nabla_{D,D})\circ(t_{D% ,D}\otimes D),$ (a2-4) $t_{D,D}\circ\nabla_{D,D}=\nabla_{D,D}\circ t_{D,D}=t_{D,D}.$ (a3) There exists a morphism $t^{\prime}_{D,D}:D\otimes D\rightarrow D\otimes D$ such that: (a3-1) The morphism $p_{D,D}\circ t_{D,D}\circ i_{D,D}:D\times D\rightarrow D\times D$ is an isomorphism with inverse $p_{D,D}\circ t^{\prime}_{D,D}\circ i_{D,D}:D\times D\rightarrow D\times D$, where $p_{D,D}$ and $i_{D,D}$ are the morphisms such that $i_{D,D}\circ p_{D,D}=\nabla_{D,D}$ and $p_{D,D}\circ i_{D,D}=id_{D\times D}$ being $D\times D$ the image of $\nabla_{D,D}$. (a3-2) $t^{\prime}_{D,D}\circ\nabla_{D,D}=\nabla_{D,D}\circ t^{\prime}_{D,D}=t^{\prime% }_{D,D}.$ Note that if $\nabla_{D,D}=id_{D\otimes D}$ then $t_{D,D}$ is an isomorphism and we recover the definition of Yang-Baxter operator introduced by Joyal and Street in [11]. Also, by [[1], Definition 1.2 and Proposition 1.3], we get that $t_{D,D}$ is a weak Yang-Baxter operator with associated idempotent $\nabla_{D,D}$ if and only if so is $t^{\prime}_{D,D}.$ Moreover, in this case ${t^{\prime}}_{D,D}\circ t_{D,D}=t_{D,D}\circ{t^{\prime}}_{D,D}=\nabla_{D,D}.$ Finally, using the identities (2)-(5) of [1] we obtain: $(D\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t^{\prime}_{D,D})=(t^{% \prime}_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes D),$ $(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\otimes D)=(D% \otimes t^{\prime}_{D,D})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D,D}),$ $(D\otimes t^{\prime}_{D,D})\circ(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t_{D% ,D})=(t_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t^{\prime}_{D,D})\circ(t^{\prime}_{D,D}% \otimes D),$ $(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t^{\prime}_{D,D})\circ(t_{D,D}% \otimes D)=(D\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes t^% {\prime}_{D,D}).$
Definition 2.7. Let $D$ be a WBHA. The category of left-left Yetter-Drinfeld modules is that whose objects are the class ${}_{D}^{D}\mathcal{YD}$ and whose morphisms between objects are those in the conditions of Definition 2.5. It will be denoted also by ${}^{D}_{D}\mathcal{YD}$.
Definition 1.9. Let $D$ be a WBHA and let $M$ be an object of $\mathcal{C}.$ A weak operator between $M$ and $D,$ (from now on referred as $(M,D)$-WO) is defined as a quadruple $(r_{M},r_{M}^{\prime},s_{M},s_{M}^{\prime})$ comprised of four morphisms in $\mathcal{C}$: $r_{M}:M\otimes D\rightarrow D\otimes M,\qquad r_{M}^{\prime}:D\otimes M% \rightarrow M\otimes D,$ $s_{M}:D\otimes M\rightarrow M\otimes D,\qquad s_{M}^{\prime}:M\otimes D% \rightarrow D\otimes M,$ satisfying the following compatibility conditions: (c1) Compatibility with the weak Yang-Baxter operator: (c1-1) $(D\otimes r_{M})\circ(r_{M}\otimes D)\circ(M\otimes t_{D,D})=(t_{D,D}\otimes M% )\circ(D\otimes r_{M})\circ(r_{M}\otimes D),$ (c1-2) $(r_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes r_{M}^{\prime})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes M)% =(M\otimes t_{D,D})\circ(r_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes r_{M}^{\prime}),$ (c1-3) $(s_{M}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes s_{M})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes M)=(M\otimes t_{D,D}% )\circ(s_{M}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes s_{M}),$ (c1-4) $(D\otimes s_{M}^{\prime})\circ(s_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D)\circ(M\otimes t_{D,D})% =(t_{D,D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes s_{M}^{\prime})\circ(s_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D).$ The analogous equalities with $t^{\prime}_{D,D}$ instead of $t_{D,D}$ are also required to be satisfied. (c2) Mixed Yang-Baxter equations (c2-1) $(r_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes s_{M})\circ(t_{D,D}\otimes M)=(M% \otimes t_{D,D})\circ(s_{M}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes r_{M}^{\prime}),$ (c2-2) $(s_{M}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes r_{M}^{\prime})\circ(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\otimes M)% =(M\otimes t^{\prime}_{D,D})\circ(r_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes s_{M}),$ (c2-3) $(D\otimes s_{M}^{\prime})\circ(r_{M}\otimes D)\circ(M\otimes t_{D,D})=(t_{D,D}% \otimes M)\circ(D\otimes r_{M})\circ(s_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D),$ (c2-4) $(D\otimes r_{M})\circ(s_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D)\circ(M\otimes t^{\prime}_{D,D})% =(t^{\prime}_{D,D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes s_{M}^{\prime})\circ(r_{M}\otimes D).$ We want to point out that in this case, as in general for all the mixed equations along the paper, we cannot replace $t_{D,D}$ by $t^{\prime}_{D,D}$ or $t^{\prime}_{D,D}$ by $t_{D,D}$. (c3) The morphisms: $\nabla_{r_{M}}:=r_{M}^{\prime}\circ r_{M}$, $\nabla_{r_{M}^{\prime}}:=r_{M}\circ r_{M}^{\prime}$, $\nabla_{s_{M}}:=s_{M}^{\prime}\circ s_{M}$ and $\nabla_{s_{M}^{\prime}}:=s_{M}\circ s_{M}^{\prime}$ satisfy (c3-1) $\nabla_{r_{M}}=(((\varepsilon_{D}\otimes M)\circ r_{M})\otimes D)\circ(M% \otimes\delta_{D})=(M\otimes\mu_{D})\circ(((r_{M}^{\prime}\circ(\eta_{D}% \otimes M))\otimes D),$ (c3-2) $\nabla_{r_{M}^{\prime}}=(D\otimes((M\otimes\varepsilon_{D})\circ r_{M}^{\prime% }))\circ(\delta_{D}\otimes M)=(\mu_{D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes(r_{M}\circ(M% \otimes\eta_{D}))),$ (c3-3) $\nabla_{s_{M}}=(D\otimes((M\otimes\varepsilon_{D})\circ s_{M}))\circ(\delta_{D% }\otimes M)=(\mu_{D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes(s_{M}^{\prime}\circ(M\otimes\eta_% {D}))),$ (c3-4) $\nabla_{s_{M}^{\prime}}=(((\varepsilon_{D}\otimes M)\circ s_{M}^{\prime})% \otimes D)\circ(M\otimes\delta_{D})=(M\otimes\mu_{D})\circ(((s_{M}\circ(\eta_{% D}\otimes M))\otimes D).$ (c4) Compatibility with the (co) multiplication: (c4-1) $r_{M}\circ(M\otimes\mu_{D})=(\mu_{D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes r_{M})\circ(r_{M}% \otimes D),$ (c4-2) $r_{M}^{\prime}\circ(\mu_{D}\otimes M)=(M\otimes\mu_{D})\circ(r_{M}^{\prime}% \otimes D)\circ(D\otimes r_{M}^{\prime}),$ (c4-3) $(D\otimes r_{M})\circ(r_{M}\otimes D)\circ(M\otimes\delta_{D})=(\delta_{D}% \otimes M)\circ r_{M},$ (c4-4) $(r_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes r_{M}^{\prime})\circ(\delta_{D}\otimes M% )=(M\otimes\delta_{D})\circ r_{M}^{\prime},$ (c4-5) $s_{M}\circ(\mu_{D}\otimes M)=(M\otimes\mu_{D})\circ(s_{M}\otimes D)\circ(D% \otimes s_{M}),$ (c4-6) $s_{M}^{\prime}\circ(M\otimes\mu_{D})=(\mu_{D}\otimes M)\circ(D\otimes s_{M}^{% \prime})\circ(s_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D),$ (c4-7) $(s_{M}\otimes D)\circ(D\otimes s_{M})\circ(\delta_{D}\otimes M)=(M\otimes% \delta_{D})\circ s_{M},$ (c4-8) $(D\otimes s_{M}^{\prime})\circ(s_{M}^{\prime}\otimes D)\circ(M\otimes\delta_{D% })=(\delta_{D}\otimes M)\circ s_{M}^{\prime}.$ (c5) Compatibility with the antipode: (c5-1) $(M\otimes\lambda_{D})\circ\nabla_{r_{M}}=\nabla_{r_{M}}\circ(M\otimes\lambda_{% D}),$ (c5-2) $(\lambda_{D}\otimes M)\circ\nabla_{r_{M}^{\prime}}=\nabla_{r_{M}^{\prime}}% \circ(\lambda_{D}\otimes M),$ (c5-3) $(\lambda_{D}\otimes M)\circ\nabla_{s_{M}}=\nabla_{s_{M}}\circ(\lambda_{D}% \otimes M),$ (c5-4) $(M\otimes\lambda_{D})\circ\nabla_{s_{M}^{\prime}}=\nabla_{s_{M}^{\prime}}\circ% (M\otimes\lambda_{D}).$
